lead_paragraph: 9 P.M. (Pivot) GARDENERS OF EDEN Kristin Davis (“Sex and the City”) travels to the David Sheldrick Wildlife Trust in Kenya, where conservationists are battling the poaching of elephants for the illegal ivory trade while rescuing orphaned offspring that are eventually returned to the wild. (Above, an orphan visiting a Trust keeper, Benjamin Kyalo.) She also examines the elephant’s role in maintaining the habitats that support it and other species.

abstract: Hillary Rodham Clinton continues to face questions on how to respond to the policies of former President Bill Clinton.
snippet: Hillary Rodham Clinton continues to face questions on how to respond to the policies of former President Bill Clinton.
lead_paragraph: Good Friday morning from Washington. Republicans are gathering in South Carolina, and Senator Bernie Sanders of Vermont made his candidacy for president official. All eyes remain on Hillary Rodham Clinton, who must decide not only how to respond to him, but continues to face questions on how to respond to the policies of former President Bill Clinton.

abstract: Most recent drug development in the U.S. has been done through specially approved pathways, and two more may be added.
snippet: Most recent drug development in the U.S. has been done through specially approved pathways, and two more may be added.
lead_paragraph: Congress has over the past few decades passed a series of special approval pathways for important drugs that treat life-threatening or rare diseases. This week, a new bill introduced in the House could add two more.

headline_main: Speedy Drug Approvals Have Become the Rule, Not the Exception

abstract: As the streets of Baltimore erupt in protests, and questions about race, poverty and the prison population tower over the political landscape, the halcyon years of the tough-on-crime Bill Clinton administration look less idyllic.
snippet: As the streets of Baltimore erupt in protests, and questions about race, poverty and the prison population tower over the political landscape, the halcyon years of the tough-on-crime Bill Clinton administration look less idyllic.
lead_paragraph: It was a favorite riposte of Hillary Rodham Clinton’s in her 2008 presidential campaign: “I always wonder what part of the 1990s they didn’t like,” she would say about critics who brought up her husband’s administration, “the peace or the prosperity?”

abstract: With their spouses, they made up a friendly foursome for more than 30 years. Now, after being widowed, Leonard Lauder and Judy Glickman are moving on. Together.

abstract: Cellphones and drugs are among the forbidden items making their way to inmates in a high-tech version of smuggling a file in a birthday cake.
snippet: Cellphones and drugs are among the forbidden items making their way to inmates in a high-tech version of smuggling a file in a birthday cake.
lead_paragraph: BISHOPVILLE, S.C. — During the graveyard shift at 1:44 a.m., security cameras at the prison here picked up the blinking lights of an unidentified flying object approaching the facility’s fence.

abstract: A city in which both the mayor and the police commissioner are black will be compared with white-governed cities in how it handles the death of Mr. Gray, who was restrained by the police.
snippet: A city in which both the mayor and the police commissioner are black will be compared with white-governed cities in how it handles the death of Mr. Gray, who was restrained by the police.
lead_paragraph: BALTIMORE — In life, friends say, Freddie Gray was an easygoing, slender young man who liked girls and partying here in Sandtown, a section of west Baltimore pocked by boarded-up rowhouses and known to the police for drug dealing and crime.

headline_print_headline: Another City, Another Death in Public Eye
byline_original: By Sheryl Gay Stolberg and Ron Nixon

abstract: The retail tycoon, who turned Sotheby’s into a global power for art sales, went to prison in a price-fixing scandal involving Christie’s that, prosecutors said, cheated buyers and sellers out of $100 million.
snippet: The retail tycoon, who turned Sotheby’s into a global power for art sales, went to prison in a price-fixing scandal involving Christie’s that, prosecutors said, cheated buyers and sellers out of $100 million.
lead_paragraph: A. Alfred Taubman, an art collector and shopping-mall tycoon who sold Renoirs and root beer with equal panache and turned a sleepy Sotheby’s auction house into a global power of art sales, but went to prison in a commission-fixing scandal involving its archrival Christie’s, died on Friday at his home in Bloomfield Hills, Mich. He was 91.
